It’s one of those days. It happens to the best of us for a variety of reasons. And while beating up on yourself may be your favorite masochistic activity… it’s not a good use of your energy! 😉

When the day gets away from you, do this:
1. Stop. 🛑 Unless it’s urgently urgent… stop and write down what you absolutely must do today to move yourself forward - even a millimeter - to your goal. Take at least 30 minutes to get that done.
2. When you’re done with the day, revisit all you’ve done. This is where time tracking comes in handy. You’ll notice that while you may have not stuck to your plan, you got some important things done!
3. 📝 Re-plan tomorrow by incorporating visualization. Prioritize the 2-3 things you MUST get done tomorrow and start with them. Visualize where you will be doing them, your mood (calm, accomplished, etc.) and with how much ease you’re getting them done. Your brain 🧠 adopts what you tell it as the truth.

And remember, being kind to yourself is important but… being optimistically realistic with yourself is most productive. Look at the data - your time sheet, your to-do list, etc. - examine and re-evaluate. 💪

#mondaymantra #mondaze #productivitytips #productivityhabits #timemanagement

🧠 Trauma is not what actually happens to you - it’s the story your brain creates connecting events that shock your system to past experiences. And every time you recall the event, it creates a different story! (Which is why eyewitness testimony is unreliable.)

Holding onto trauma - endlessly discussing with friends, making your therapist rich, replaying it in your head, making it part of your identity - has shown to expose people to a significantly higher chance of disease 🦠 including autoimmune, GI issues, and cancer. While processing unnerving events is important, doing so within a SET amount of time can - quite literally - save your life. Or at the very least, your health.

🫐 P.S. While significant disturbances to our stasis may have us reaching for comfort food (guilty!), the best foods to eat during this time are antioxidants: blueberries, açaí, and mood-boosting citrus 🍊 are great options.

The faster you grow through it, the better.

#traumahealing #traumarecovery #traumainformed #traumatologia #neuroscience #neurodiversity #healingvibrations

❌Don’t mistake knowledge for expertise.

Many people waste their potential because they spend too much time ‘learning’ and not enough time doing.

Yes, I said it.

I used to read 3 books a week.

It made me feel great, but for all the wrong reasons. I was doing the “right thing,” not the productive thing.

In fact, the variety of information was taking away from my progress. It is impractical to implement it all. 

And while I revisit classics like Think & Grow Rich regularly, I don’t remember 10% of ‘practical’ books I read in my life. 

But I do remember every single thing I learned jumping into businesses before I knew even 10% of what I needed to know to run them.

👉🏻 Doing taught me how to learn in a way that produces results faster.

When I don’t know how to do something, I look up how to do that exact thing or ask an expert. With resources like ChatGPT, it’s easier than ever.

Then I do it.

Then I improve it.

Learning that new skill usually takes me less time than reading a book.

💯If you are finding yourself hiding behind knowledge, spend a week or two just implementing what you’ve learned. You will likely find that you only read half the story. The rest can only be learned through doing.

#kriscent #coaye

As an entrepreneur, refreshing your vision every 6 to 12 months is not ideal - it’s mandatory.

Without it, you have no destination and no compass 🧭 to navigate the ever-changing waters.

So, how do you do it? First, let’s see how NOT to do it.

❌Vision Boards 

Only a small percentage of people are helped by vision boards. And even a smaller percentage know why vision boards help them.

Here’s why: To get to where you want to be, you must first get your brain 🧠 to believe it to be true.

That process is simple, but not always easy.

Looking at pictures of what you want CAN help, but only… ONLY… if you can actually believe in achieving it. 

🏃‍♀️ Internal visualization is a more powerful tool because it is your own mind creating the images. That’s why so many athletes use it successfully.

BUT… the real reason behind why this works well for athletes is because as they visualize the movements, it activates areas of the brain responsible for muscle activity. (We have seen this with our own EEG testing.) Essentially, their brain is now convinced that they have accomplished the feat successfully.

🧐 So, how can a non-athlete visualize effectively? By activating their mind-muscle connection. 

One of the most powerful exercises I assign to my coaching clients (that 80% fight me on) is a neuro-based visualization exercise that has 100% success rate. 

Moreover, it re-establishes purpose for those experiencing the “now what?” moment in their lives.

While I’m NOT ❌ taking on any new coaching clients at the moment, I am considering holding a 20-minute group sessions to share this exercise that has gotten me everything I ever believed I wanted.

If you’d like to join, DM me.

#kriscent #visualization

The best version of yourself is not a mythical creature. 🧜‍♀️

While many focus on mastering the mind - an interpretation of the ‘person’ that we are - it’s the brain that is responsible for who you know yourself to be.

That ‘person’ you are is a hastily-crafted combination of your past, which the brain has stored AND dispersed into your muscle memory.

👻 Yes, you are a walking ghost of all the past experiences you have not rewritten.

________

WHERE TO START

Meet your best self. Visualizing a conversation with your higher self will help you see points A and B.
📍 Point A - Who you are.
📍 Point B - Who you can be.

From there, it’s the simple (but not easy) process of getting from point A to B. 

HINT: If it took you 30 years to be a certain way, don’t expect to change it in a day!
________

Do you? Do you have a strategic plan B? (And I’m not just talking caffeine.)

That’s the difference between business owners and entrepreneurs.

Business owners give their all to a business, attaching themselves as if it were a child whose survival is dependent on them (because it is). Their plan B may exist within that ecosystem, but rarely outside of it.

There is a fine line between the two and then, there is the transition period.

😵There’s a silent killer in business. It seems innocent, even *recommended*, but it’s secretly:

⬇️ Draining your energy.
⬇️ Distracting you from profitable projects.
⬇️ Driving your team crazy.
⬇️ Misallocating your resources. 
⬇️ Preventing you from delivering RESULTS a.k.a. failure.

It’s not AI. Not strategy. Not even your product.

⚠️ It’s saying YES. Every. Single. Time. to what your clients want.

We’re taught that “the customer is always right” and success is keeping the client happy. While that logic may work in some product-based businesses, it drains service-based businesses.

🧠 Neuroscience shows our brain is wired to please, an evolutionary tool for group cohesion. But in the modern business world? That’s a trap.

👇When facing a counterproductive request, remember:

1️⃣ You’re the Pro: They came to you for a reason. Trust yourself enough to speak up. At the end of the day, you will be taking responsibility for the outcome so you might as well go with your gut.

2️⃣ Guide with Purpose: Listen, but also lead. Collaborate with your clients by agreeing on the outcome they want and explaining why your method may be a better way of getting there.

3️⃣ Know When (and How) to Say No. No lasting victory has ever come out of place of fear. If after a collaborative effort, you still feel that the client’s ask is severely counterproductive and may reflect poorly on you in the end, excuse yourself from the project. The client will either respect you for it, or you will have space for a new client that aligns better with your expertise. 

Of course, know when to pick your battles.

“Trust in Expertise”, Business Insight Today, 2020.

👇Impressing people looks like…

🗂️First, SAVE this post because if you’re an entrepreneur, you may not understand it NOW but you WILL want to come back to it. 

Impressing people does NOT ❌ always look like:
🏎️ Driving expensive cars
🏘️ Living in a mansion
💎 Wearing couture and diamonds

I bought my first 5-figure watch because I LOVED it. I lived in the best building because the view INSPIRED me. I never cared what people thought about those aspects of me.

⚠️ So I thought I was safe from the need to impress people - the need to be seen, heard and respected.

Instead, seeking approval looked like this:
😵‍💫 Being mortified when things went wrong to the point of feeling paralyzed - even when I couldn’t have prevented them. 
😵‍💫 Almost dying from septicemia because client success somehow trumped my being alive.
😵‍💫 Losing $100’s of thousands trying to ‘help’ people a.k.a. wanting to be seen as a hero.

If you don’t think that the need to impress is something you ‘suffer’ from, consider this:

🧠 Neuro-wise, seeking approval stimulates the same areas of the brain as addiction. You crave it, but it’s never truly fulfilling.

👇👇So, here’s to breaking free:

1️⃣Keep the Core: Write down your own rules to life! As you grow through situations, update those rules with a clear head. Stay grounded in your values, and deny anyone who does not respect them.

3️⃣ Just Say “No”: This would’ve saved me so much trouble, time and money… Give yourself 3-6 months to focus solely on establishing and learning to trust your ground rules. Say “no” to anything that even remotely feels like it’s trespassing those rules or gives you an uneasy feeling in your chest.

4️⃣ Reflect: Regularly check in with yourself. I mean REGULARLY.

👇How much $$$ have you spent in testing visuals?

👇 WAIT - This is why:

From a neuropsychological perspective, our brains need time to process information, weigh pros and cons, and assess potential outcomes. This isn’t just about intuition; it’s how our cognitive machinery operates.

... Because when rushed:
❌ The amygdala, our emotional center, can hijack decision-making, leading to impulsive choices.
❌ We may miss details as our prefrontal cortex — responsible for planning and decision-making — gets overwhelmed.
❌ Cognitive biases can cloud our judgment more easily.

But when you give yourself time:
✅ Neurotransmitters have time to balance, leading to clearer thinking.
✅ Neural pathways process and connect information for a well-rounded perspectives.
✅ The brain integrates emotion and logic, fostering decisions that resonate holistically.

So, next time you’re at a crossroads, remember: Not choosing *now* may be the best choice for later. By letting your brain work optimally, you set yourself up for success.

🧠 Our brains are wired to pick up non-verbal cues, often before words are even processed. In fact, over 55% of our communication is non-verbal.
________

For National Body Language Day, here are a few popular body language nuances to be aware of:

👁️ Avoiding Eye Contact: Not always deception. Sometimes, it’s just the brain diving deep to retrieve memories or process complex thoughts.

💪 Crossed Arms: Many believe it’s a defensive gesture. But did you know it could also be self-comfort? Our brain sometimes seeks tactile feedback for assurance.

🫰Fidgeting: Often seen as nervousness. Yet, it can also be a brain’s way of channeling excess energy and enhancing focus.

Always couple body language ‘facts’ with context.

🧠 As we open the door to 2024, here are 17 pieces of advice from your brain (aka rooted in neuropsychology):

1. Do what you’re avoiding first. Procrastination is a compass. 

2. Prioritize brain workouts. Apps like Lumosity are easy, fun ways to train your brain every day.

3. Practice contentment. Good decisions are made from a place of peaceful indifference, not emotional charge.

4. Visualize with purpose. Your brain will believe anything you tell it with conviction and consistency.

5. Eat brain food. Opt for a real-food diet rich in omega-3’s. 

6. Plan less, accomplish more. 

7. If you find fault with someone else, check if you need to work on that fault yourself.

8. Record yourself throughout the day doing normal tasks and play it back. The ‘mirror effect’ will help you align your behavior with your internal standards.

9. When someone is talking to you, repeat what they’re saying in your head. It makes you an active listener.

10. Have big dreams, but set micro goals. (Especially if you are paralyzed by indecision).

11. Sleep enough hours for your age and activity level. Every night. 

12. Say “no” more. Preserve your mental energy.

13. Start each day with jumping jacks and gratitude journaling. It takes 5 minutes.

14. Drink enough water for your activity level. 

15. When presented with an opportunity, run it by an expert, a good friend and someone who is skeptical about everything.

16. Time each task you do and become hyper aware of what drains your time unnecessarily. 

17. Try on advice like an outfit. If it doesn’t fit, take it off.
